      <hedline>
        <hl1>Libraries and Catalogs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Ettinger letter, commenting on Aug 10 article, says although the Internet can often be a useful and expedient supplement, it does not supplant traditional library research methods</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As an academic librarian at a major university, I identify completely with those educators who lament the lackadaisical approach to research adopted by many students. Although the Internet can often be a useful and expedient supplement, it does not supplant traditional library research methods. Convincing students of this fact is one of the ongoing challenges of contemporary librarianship.</p>
        <p>DAVID ETTINGER, PH.D.  Washington</p>
        <p>The writer is the international affairs and political science librarian at the Gelman Library at George Washington University.</p>
      </block>
